t Composer\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best International Success\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[NRJ Music Awards]]\n| 2019\n| International Breakthrough of the Year\n| {{nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{Cite web|title=NRJ Music Awards 2019 : Ang\u00e8le, Rom\u00e9o Elvis et Lil Nas X dominent la liste des nomm\u00e9s|publisher=Ozap|url=https://www.ozap.com/actu/nrj-music-awards-2019-angele-romeo-elvis-et-lil-nas-x-dominent-la-liste-des-nommes/584030 |language=French|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[:sv:P3 Guld|P3 Guld]]\n| 2020\n| \"[[Don't Call Me Up]]\"\n| Song of the Year\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=3964&artikel=7322693 |title=H\u00e4r \u00e4r artisterna som \u00e4r nominerade till P3 Guld 2020|work=sverigesradio.se|date=28 November 2019|access-date=28 November 2019|language=sv}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Silver Clef Award]]\n| 2019\n| Herself\n| Best Newcomer\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nordoff-robbins.org.uk/events/the-o2-silver-clef-awards/ |title=O2 Silver Clef Awards|website=Nordoff Robbins|access-date=14 July 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"5\"| [[Urban Music Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2018\n| Herself\n| Best Female Act\n| {{nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"|<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.urbanmusicawards.co/16th-annual-urban-music-awards-nominations-announced/ |title=16th annual Urban Music Awards nominations announced|date=22 October 2018|work=Urban Music Awards}}</ref>\n|-\n| \"My Lover\" {{small|(with [[Not3s]])}}\n| Best Music Video\n| {{nominated}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2020\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Herself\n| Best Female Act\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\"|<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.urbanmusicawards.co/mabel-earns-x3-nominations-at-the-17th-annual-urban-music-awards-2020/ |title=Mabel earns x3 nominations at the 17th annual Urban Music Awards 2020|date=25 November 2019|work=Urban Music Awards}}</ref>\n|-\n| Artist of the Year (UK)\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| \"[[Don't Call Me Up]]\"\n| Best Music Video\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist-ua}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Mabel McVey|nowrap=yes}}\n* {{Official website|mabelofficial.com}}\n* {{twitter|id=Mabel|name=Mabel}}\n\n{{Mabel}}\n<br/>\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British contemporary R&B singers]]\n[[Category:Black British singers]]\n[[Category:Polydor Records artists]]\n[[Category:Singers from London]]\n[[Category:English people of Swedish descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Sierra Leonean descent]]\n[[Category:English female pop singers]]\n[[Category:People from M\u00e1laga]]\n[[Category:21st-century English women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century English singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc}}\n{{short description|English singer and songwriter}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Mabel\n| image              = Mabel-42617.jpg\n| image_size         = 220px\n| caption            = Mabel in September 2018\n| birth_name         = Mabel Alabama-Pearl McVey<ref name=\"independent\"/>\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1996|2|20}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://planetradio.co.uk/hits-radio/entertainment/music/mabel-singer/|title=Everything you need to know about Mabel the singer|work=[[Hits Radio]]|accessdate=19 February 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[M\u00e1laga]], Spain\n| citizenship        = {{hlist|British|Swedish|Spanish}}\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter}}\n| parents            = [[Cameron McVey]]<br>[[Neneh Cherry]]\n| relatives          = {{plainlist|\n*[[Marlon Roudette]] (half-brother)\n*[[Eagle-Eye Cherry]] (uncle)\n*[[Don Cherry (trumpeter)|Don Cherry]] (step-grandfather)\n}}\n| years_active       = 2015\u2013present\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background         = solo_singer\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n*[[Pop music|Pop]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amp.theguardian.com/music/2019/aug/01/mabel-high-expectations-review|title=Mabel: High Expectations review \u2013 confident pop lacks personality {{!}} Music {{!}} The Guardian|website=amp.theguardian.com|access-date=2019-08-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://crackmagazine.net/article/aesthetic/aesthetic-mabel/|title=Aesthetic: Mabel|website=Crack Magazine|access-date=2019-08-07}}</ref>\n*[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/may/03/one-to-watch-mabel-r-and-b-singer-bedroom-ep-neneh-cherry|title=One to Watch: Mabel, R&B Singer|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=May 3, 2018|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n| instrument       = Vocals, piano\n| label            = [[Polydor Records|Polydor]]\n| website          = {{URL|http://www.mabelofficial.com/|Official website}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Mabel Alabama-Pearl McVey'''<ref name=\"independent\"/> (born 20 February 1996) is an English singer and songwriter. In 2017, she had her mainstream breakthrough with \"[[Finders Keepers (Mabel song)|Finders Keepers]]\", peaking at number eight on the [[UK Singles Chart]]. Her debut studio album, ''[[High Expectations]]'', was released in August 2019 and entered the [[UK Albums Chart]] at number three. It spawned the UK top-10 singles \"[[Don't Call Me Up]]\" and \"[[Mad Love (Mabel song)|Mad Love]]\". Mabel has received numerous [[#Awards and nominations|awards and accolades]], including the [[Premios 40 Principales for Best International New Artist]] in 2019 and the [[Brit Award for British Female Solo Artist]] in 2020.\n\n==Early life==\nMabel Alabama-Pearl McVey was born in [[M\u00e1laga]] on 20 February 1996.<ref name=\"independent\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/she-wore-lycra-over-her-pregnant-tummy-in-1988-she-has-her-kids-to-mock-her-if-she-gets-too-1313469.html|title=She wore Lycra over her pregnant tummy in 1988; she has her kids to|date=1996-12-08|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Mabel|url=https://www.mabelofficial.com/about/ |website=Mabel Official Website |accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref> She is the daughter of Swedish singer [[Neneh Cherry]] and English record producer [[Cameron McVey]]. Her step-grandfather is American jazz trumpeter [[Don Cherry (trumpeter)|Don Cherry]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/article/who-is-mabel-mcvey|title=Who's That Girl?|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/may/03/one-to-watch-mabel-r-and-b-singer-bedroom-ep-neneh-cherry|title=One to watch: Mabel|last=Snapes|first=Laura|date=7 May 2017|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref> Her half-brother is the former [[Mattafix]] singer [[Marlon Roudette]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.capitalfm.com/artists/mabel/brother-famous-singer-video/|title=People Have Only Just Realised Mabel's Brother Is This Famous Singer|website=Capital|language=en|access-date=2019-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/esmagazine/why-neneh-cherrys-daughter-mabel-mcvey-is-making-her-own-way-in-the-music-world-a3612131.html|title=Why Mabel McVey is making her own way in the music world|date=2017-08-16|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=2019-03-31}}</ref> She holds British, Swedish, and Spanish citizenship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wanacorp.fr/mabel-mcvey-english-version/|title=Mabel McVey, the multicultural artist who {{sic|suceeds|nolink=y}} brilliantly in the UK ! {{!}}|access-date=2019-06-07|date=28 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMabel's career began in 2015 with her debut single, \"Know Me Better\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2015/07/13/mabel-know-me-better|title=Listen To Mabel's Tender, Truth-Telling Debut Single, Know Me Better |website=The FADER}}</ref> In May 2017, she released \"[[Finders Keepers (Mabel song)|Finders Keepers]]\" featuring British rapper Kojo Funds, which reached the Top 10 of the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-radar/mabel-finders-keepers-listen-2162817|title=Mabel breaks down her breakout chart hit 'Finders Keepers'|first=Thomas|last=Smith|date=23 November 2017|website=NME}}</ref> Later in 2017, she released her debut [[extended play]] ''Bedroom'', as well as a mixtape, ''[[Ivy to Roses]]''. Mabel then opened for English singer [[Harry Styles]] during the European part of the second leg of a tour in the support of his [[Harry Styles (album)|debut studio album]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/harry_styles/status/936079518275575809?lang=en|title=Harry Styles. on Twitter|via=Twitter|accessdate=25 March 2018}}</ref> After her tour with Styles, she embarked on her own headline tour through the United Kingdom and Europe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/mabel-announces-massive-uk-tour-2343847|title=Mabel announces massive UK tour|last=Aubrey|first=Elizabeth|date=2018-06-25|website=NME|accessdate=17 January 2019}}</ref> In 2018, she was featured on \"[[Ring Ring (Jax Jones song)|Ring Ring]]\" alongside American rapper [[Rich the Kid]] and British DJ [[Jax Jones]]. Mabel then re-released her mixtape ''Ivy to Roses'' with a new cover art, and included songs that had been released since the initial release. Later that year, she co-wrote \"Blind\", a song for British girl group [[Four of Diamonds]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pmstudio.com/music/music.html?page=20181210-8475|title=Four Of Diamonds Premieres New Music Video for \"Blind\"|website=pm studio world wide news|language=ja|access-date=2019-05-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://celebmix.com/four-of-diamonds-new-single-blind/|title=Four of Diamonds release infectious new single 'Blind'|date=2018-12-01|website=CelebMix|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-05-26}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, Mabel was nominated for [[Brit Award for British Breakthrough Act|British Breakthrough Act]] at the [[2019 Brit Awards|39th Brit Awards]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brits.co.uk/news/2018-critics-choice-shortlist-announced|title=2018 Critics' Choice shortlist announced|website=BRIT Awards|language=en|access-date=2019-02-01}}</ref> and released \"[[Don't Call Me Up]]\", which debuted at number 11 on the UK Singles Chart. The song peaked at number three, becoming her highest-charting single to date.<ref name=\"UK\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/52386/mabel/|title=Mabel {{!}} full Official Chart history|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=30 June 2018}}</ref> On 7 June 2019, she released \"[[Mad Love (Mabel song)|Mad Love]]\", the second single from her debut studio album, ''[[High Expectations]]''. The song debuted at number 18 in the UK, later peaking at number 8.<ref name=\"UK\"/> From 2019 to 2020, Mabel will embark on the [[High Expectations Tour]] across North America, the United Kingdom and Europe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.list.co.uk/article/109798-mabel-announces-2020-uk-tour-dates-find-out-how-to-get-tickets/|title=Mabel announces 2020 UK tour dates, find out how to get tickets|date=2019-07-18|website=The List|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Mabel discography}}\n* ''[[High Expectations]]'' (2019)\n\n==Concert tours==\n===Headlining===\n* High Expectations Tour (2020)\n\n===Supporting===\n* [[Harry Styles: Live on Tour]] (2018)\n* [[LANY]]: Thrilla in Manila (2019)\n* [[Free Spirit World Tour|Khalid: Free Spirit World Tour]] (2019)\n*Harry Styles: [[Love On Tour]] (2020)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Harry_Styles/status/1237457039862845440|title=LOVE ON TOUR 2020...|last=Styles|first=Harry|date=2020-03-10|website=Twitter|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{| class=\