-9358392 |website=Channel NewsAsia |accessdate=13 June 2019 |date=30 October 2017}}</ref> \n* 31 October \u2013 [[Singapore Changi Airport Terminal 4|Changi Airport Terminal 4]] begins operations.<ref>{{cite web |title=Changi Airport\u2019s Terminal 4 to open on Oct 31 |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/nine-airlines-operate-changi-airport-t4-set-open-oct-31 |website=Today |accessdate=6 September 2019 |date=6 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===November===\n* 6 November \u2013 Radio station 938LIVE is rebranded to [[CNA938|938Now]].\n* 7 November \u2013 Amendments are passed to raise the [[smoking age]] from 18 to 21 in stages, as well as ban people from buying, using and owning imitation tobacco products such as e-cigarettes, e-cigars and e-pipes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/legal-age-for-smoking-to-be-gradually-raised-from-18-to-21-9383644|title=Legal age for smoking to be gradually raised from 18 to 21|work=CNA|access-date=28 April 2019|language=en}}</ref>\n* 8 November \u2013 All healthcare providers will soon be required to contribute to the National Electronic Health Record, an online health record in operation since 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/national-electronic-health-record-mandatory-clinics-9385666|title=National electronic patient database soon to be mandatory for healthcare providers|date=2017-11-08|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2019-07-11}}</ref>\n* 11 November \u2013 The first active aging hub officially opened in Kwong Wai Shiu Hospital.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Abdullah |first1=Zhaki |title=Kwong Wai Shiu Hospital officially opens first active ageing hub |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/kwong-wai-shiu-hospital-officially-opens-first-active-ageing-hub |accessdate=7 July 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=11 November 2018}}</ref>\n* 15 November \u2013 A [[Joo Koon train collision|train collision]] along the [[East West MRT Line]] between [[Joo Koon MRT station|Joo Koon]] and [[Gul Circle MRT station|Gul Circle]]; this was only the second train collision in the MRT history to have happen in its 30-year history, after the 1993 [[Clementi rail accident]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/smrt-collision-second-incident-in-mrts-30-year-history|title=SMRT collision second incident in MRT's 30-year history|date=15 November 2017|work=The Straits Times|access-date=26 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201045029/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/smrt-collision-second-incident-in-mrts-30-year-history|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live|language=en|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 16 November \u2013 All new homes are required to have [[smoke detectors]] (also known as Home Fire Alarm Device (HFAD)) from June 2018, allowing for early fire alerts. Existing home owners are encouraged to install such devices.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ng |first1=Jun Sen |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/smoke-detectors-mandatory-in-all-new-homes-from-june-2018-existing-homeowners-also-urged |title=Smoke detectors mandatory in all new homes from June 2018; existing home owners also urged to comply |website=The Straits Times |access-date=9 November 2019 |date=16 November 2017}}</ref>\n* 20 November \u2013 The second phase of the Deep Tunnel Sewerage System starts construction. It will mainly serve western Singapore, to be completed by 2025.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/environment/work-starts-on-65b-deep-underground-tunnels-to-transport-used-water-freeing-up|title=Work starts on $6.5b deep underground tunnels to transport used water, freeing up land above for redevelopment|date=20 November 2017|work=The Straits Times|access-date=6 June 2019}}</ref>\n* 23 November \u2013 Those born before 1 January 1962 will be able re-register their NRIC in an optional exercise come next year.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cheow |first1=Sue-Ann |title=Optional NRIC re-registration for those born before Jan 1, 1962 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/optional-nric-re-registration-for-those-born-before-jan-1-1962 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=27 December 2019 |date=23 November 2017}}</ref>\n* 24 November \u2013 The Punggol Polyclinic opens.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/punggol-polyclinic-to-open-on-nov-24|title=Punggol Polyclinic to open on Nov 24 |publisher=The Straits Times|date=22 November 2017|accessdate=12 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 25 November \u2013 [[National Parks Board|NParks]] announced that [[Sembawang Hot Spring Park]] will be developed into a public park for everyone to enjoy. The works will finish in 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/sembawang-hot-spring-to-be-developed-into-1-hectare-park-by-2019-9439366|title=Sembawang Hot Spring to be developed into 1-hectare park by 2019|date=25 November 2017|work=CNA|access-date=5 July 2019|language=en-SG}}</ref>\n\n===December===\n* 1 December \u2013 [[Singapore Civil Defence Force]] ambulances can now run red lights and make unauthorised U-turns during emergencies.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/ambulances-red-lights-unauthorised-u-turns-scdf-9382756 |title=Ambulances can legally run red lights and make unauthorised U-turns from Dec 1 |website=Channel NewsAsia |access-date=9 November 2019 |date=7 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Seow |first1=Bei Yi |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/ambulances-to-be-exempted-from-rules-that-prohibit-running-red-lights-unauthorised-u-turns |title=Ambulances to be allowed to run a red light and make unauthorised U-turns |website=The Straits Times |access-date=9 November 2019 |date=7 November 2017}}</ref>\n* 8 December \u2013 Zero Mobile launches in Singapore as the second [[mobile virtual network operator]] (MVNO).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tham |first1=Irene |title=New virtual telco Zero Mobile to launch with unusual promotion |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/tech/new-virtual-telco-zero-mobile-to-launch-with-unusual-promotion |accessdate=7 July 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=8 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 9 December \u2013 The 5-year Bus Service Enhancement Programme (BSEP) is completed, costing [[S$]]1.1b. The enhancements injected 1,000 buses and introduced 80 new services.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Zaccheus |first1=Melody |title=$1.1b enhancement of bus services complete |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/11b-enhancement-of-bus-services-complete |publisher=The Straits Times |accessdate=8 July 2019 |date=10 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 12 December \u2013 \n**[[BlueSG]] launches Singapore's first electric car sharing programme.<ref>{{cite web |title=Singapore's first electric car-sharing service rolls out with 80 vehicles |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/singapore-s-first-electric-car-sharing-service-rolls-out-with-80-9492380 |website=CNA |date=12 December 2017 |accessdate=27 June 2019}}</ref>\n**The Government has decided to partially conserve [[Dakota Crescent]], one of the oldest housing estates in Singapore.<ref>{{cite web |title=Partial conservation of Dakota Crescent gives heritage enthusiasts hope |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/partial-conservation-dakota-crescent-gives-heritage-enthusiasts-hope |website=Today |accessdate=5 May 2019 |date=12 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 15 December \u2013 After a week's delay, the first Prudential Marina Bay Carnival opens as Singapore's biggest carnival.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/marina-bay-carnival-opens-after-weeks-delay |title=Marina Bay carnival opens after week's delay |website=The Straits Times |date=15 December 2017 |access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref> The carnival runs for about four months until 1 April 2018. By then, a total of 1.4 million people have visited the Carnival.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Tee |first1=Cheryl |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/14-million-people-visited-the-prudential-carnival-which-ended-its-run-on |title=1.4 million people visited the Prudential Carnival which ended its run on April 1 |website=The Straits Times |date=3 April 2018 |access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n* 18 December - The [[Immigration and Checkpoints Authority]] will introduce e-PR system for permanent residency applications, first announced on 2 November.<ref>{{cite web |title=ICA to roll out electronic system for permanent residency applications |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/ica-to-roll-out-electronic-system-for-permanent-residency-9367982 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=31 December 2019 |date=2 November 2017}}</ref>\n* 19 December \u2013 [[Singapore Power]] announced that the North-South, East-West and Jurong Island Cable Tunnels will progressively start operations from end-2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/singapore-s-deepest-cable-tunnel-system-to-transmit-electricity-9510330|title=Singapore's deepest cable tunnel system to transmit electricity from end-2018|date=19 December 2017|work=CNA|access-date=6 June 2019}}</ref>\n* 20 December \u2013 Parking.sg is extended to those using motorcycles and heavy vehicles, making it available for all vehicle users at all car parks.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/parking-sg-app-to-be-available-for-motorcycles-heavy-vehicles-9509384 |title=Parking.sg app to be available for motorcycles, heavy vehicles from Dec 20 |website=Channel NewsAsia |access-date=9 November 2019 |date=19 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 22 December \u2013 [[Keppel Corporation|Keppel O&M]] agrees to pay up to US$422m in fines for a bribery case to US, Brazilian and Singapore authorities in a plea deal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/business/companies-markets/keppel-om-to-pay-us422m-in-fines-to-settle-bribery-probe|title=Keppel O&M to pay US$422m in fines to settle bribery probe|date=23 December 2017|work=The Straits Times|access-date=24 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180924145628/https://www.straitstimes.com/business/companies-markets/keppel-om-to-pay-us422m-in-fines-to-settle-bribery-probe|archive-date=24 September 2018|url-status=live|language=en|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Deaths==\n*16 January \u2013 [[Amin Nasir]], football player (b. 1968).\n*19 January \u2013 Juanita Melson, DJ and MRT announcer (b. 1944).<ref>{{cite web |title=Former voice of MRT announcements Juanita Melson dies |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/former-voice-of-mrt-announcements-juanita-melson-dies |publisher=The Straits Times |date=23 January 2017 |accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref>\n*26 January \u2013 Tan See Lai, educator, newscaster (b. 1934).<ref>{{cite web |title=Dozens pay respects to pioneer educator, newscaster Tan See Lai |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/dozens-pay-respects-to-pioneer-educator-newscaster-tan-see-lai-7561898 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=29 January 2017 |accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref>\n*4 February \u2013 [[Fong Swee Suan]], trade unionist (b. 1931).<ref>{{cite web |title=Former leftist trade unionist Fong Swee Suan dies, aged 85 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/former-leftist-trade-unionist-fong-swee-suan-dies-aged-85 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=5 February 2017 |accessdate=26 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Fong Swee Suan |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_2013-07-29_173512.html |publisher=NLB |accessdate=26 July 2019}}</ref>\n*27 February \u2013 [[Sin Kek Tong]], opposition veteran, founder of [[Singapore People's Party]] (b. 1944).<ref>{{cite web |title=Opposition veteran and Singapore People's Party founder Sin Kek Tong dies |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/opposition-veteran-and-singapore-peoples-party-founder-sin-kek-tong-dies |publisher=The Straits Times |date=1 March 2017 |accessdate=26 July 2019}}</ref>\n*17 April \u2013 [[Othman Wok]], politician and ambassador (b. 1924).<ref>{{cite web |title=Othman Wok, member of independent Singapore's first Cabinet, dies aged 92 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/othman-wok-member-of-independent-singapores-first-cabinet-dies-aged-92 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=17 April 2017 |accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Othman Wok |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_995_2009-07-01.html |publisher=NLB |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref>\n*22 April \u2013 [[Rufino Soliano]], musician (b. 1932).<ref>{{cite web |title=Rufino Soliano |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_2015-03-17_093353.html |publisher=NLB |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref>\n*11 July - [[Maurice Baker (Singapore)|Maurice Baker]], academic, diplomat (b. 1920).<ref>{{cite web |title=Maurice Baker |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1538_2009-09-10.html |website=NLB |accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n*7 September \u2013 [[Duncan Watt]], writer, newscaster (b. 1942).<ref>{{cite web |title=Writer and former newscaster Duncan Watt dies, aged 74 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/writer-and-former-newscaster-duncan-watt-has-died |publisher=The Straits Times |date=7 September 2017 |accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[2017]]\n*[[History of Singapore]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Years in Singapore}}\n{{Asia topic|2017 in}}\n\n[[Category:2017 in Singapore| ]]\n[[Category:2017 in Southeast Asia|Singapore]]\n[[Category:2010s in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Years of the 21st century in Singapore]]\n[[Category:2017 by country|Singapore]]\n", "text_old": "{{Dynamic list}}\n{{Year in Singapore|2017}}\n\nThe following lists events that happened during '''[[2017]] in the [[Singapore|Republic of Singapore]]'''.\n\n==Incumbents==\n*[[President of Singapore|President]]: [[Tony Tan Keng Yam]] {{small|(until 31 August)}}, [[J. Y. Pillay]] {{small|(Acting) (1 to 14 September)}}, [[Halimah Yacob]] {{small|(starting 14 September)}}\n*[[Prime Minister of Singapore|Prime Minister]]: [[Lee Hsien Loong]]\n\n==Events==\n===January===\n* 1 January \u2013 \n**The collection of iris images starts as amendments to the National Registration Act come into force. Some SingPost employees are appointed for that role.<ref>{{cite web |title=Authorities to collect iris scans from Singaporeans, PRs starting Jan 1 |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/authorities-to-collect-iris-scans-from-singaporeans-prs-starting-7657104 |website=Channel NewsAsia |accessdate=27 December 2019 |date=28 December 2016}}</ref>\n**The re-registration of [[National Registration Identity Card|NRICs]] starts for those aged 55 and above.<ref>{{cite web | first1=Samantha | last1=Boh | url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/nric-re-registration-for-singapore-citizens-and-prs-turning-55-years-old-from-2017 | title=NRIC re-registration for Singapore citizens and PRs turning 55 years old from 2017 | date=14 November 2016 | accessdate=27 December 2019 | website=The Straits Times}}</ref>\n**The sale of 2G phones for use in Singapore is no longer allowed, with sales for export and overseas use still allowed.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sale of 2G Mobile Devices for Local Use Will Not Be Allowed from 1 January 2017 |url=https://www.imda.gov.sg/news-and-events/Media-Room/Media-Releases/2016/sale-of-2g-mobile-devices-for-local-use-will-not-be-allowed-from-1-january-2017 |website=IMDA |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=7 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Chew |first1=Hui Min |title=No more sale of 2G mobile devices for local use from Jan 1, 2017 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/tech/smartphones/no-more-sale-of-2g-mobile-devices-for-local-use-from-jan-1-2017 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=7 December 2016}}</ref>\n* 4 January \u2013 Raffles Country Club will be acquired for the [[Kuala Lumpur-Singapore High Speed Rail]] and [[Cross Island MRT line]] Western Depot, making it the second country club affected.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/raffles-country-club-to-make-way-for-kl-singapore-high-speed-rai-7537076 |title=Raffles Country Club to make way for KL-Singapore High-Speed Rail |website=Channel NewsAsia |date=4 January 2017 |accessdate=4 August 2019}}</ref>\n* 5 January \u2013 [[Maxwell Chambers]] will be expanded to meet demand for [[dispute resolution]] services,<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Khew |first1=Carolyn |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/maxwell-chambers-to-expand-will-take-over-building-that-houses-red-dot-design |title=Maxwell Chambers to expand, will take over building that houses Red Dot Design Museum |date=5 January 2017 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=29 September 2019}}</ref> taking over the [[Red Dot|Red Dot Design Museum]], which moved to [[Marina Bay, Singapore|Marina Bay]] in end-2017.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Ang |first1=Prisca |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/red-dot-design-museum-moving-to-marina-bay|title=Red Dot Design Museum moving to Marina Bay |date=21 June 2017 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref> The expanded section is now called [[Maxwell Chambers#Maxwell Chambers Suites|Maxwell Chambers Suites]].<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Ang |first1=Prisca |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/red-dot-traffic-building-renamed-maxwell-chambers-suites |title=Red Dot Traffic Building renamed Maxwell Chambers Suites |date=22 June 2017 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref> Due to strong demand, a second annexe block of 3,500 sq ft space is also constructed on top of the original 120,000 sq ft.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlaw.gov.sg/content/minlaw/en/news/speeches/keynote-address-by-ms-indranee-rajah--senior-minister-of-state--.html |title=Ground-Breaking of 28 Maxwell Road |date=22 June 2017 |website=MinLaw |access-date=14 August 2019}}</ref>\n* 9 January \u2013 The re-employment age is raised to the age of 67 on 1 July, from 65 currently among changes to the Retirement and Re-employment Act passed. In addition, eligible employees can be re-employed by another firm, and an option to cut 10 percent of wages at age 60 is removed.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Lim |first1=Linette |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/higher-re-employment-age-passed-into-law-in-singapore-7533148 |title=Higher re-employment age passed into law in Singapore |website=Channel NewsAsia |date=9 January 2017 |access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n* 10 January \u2013 The [[Active Mobility Act]] is passed to regulate [[personal transporter|personal mobility devices]] and [[bicycles]], and sets out penalties for non-compliance.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/parliament-cycling-and-personal-mobility-devices-essential-to-countrys-car-lite-drive-says |title=Parliament: Cycling and personal mobility devices essential to country's car-lite drive, says Josephine Teo |date=10 January 2017 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=2 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 18 January \u2013 \n**A [[NEWater]] plant is launched in Changi, built on top of an existing one.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/singapore-launches-fifth-newater-plant-at-changi-boosting-treated-used-water-supply-by-10 |title=Singapore launches fifth Newater plant at Changi, boosting water supply |date=18 January 2017 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=2 July 2019}}</ref>\n**The [[Ministry of Health (Singapore)|Ministry of Health]] announced that the current six healthcare clusters will be merged into three, namely the [[National Healthcare Group]], [[SingHealth]] and [[National University Health System]]. In addition, the National University Health System will form the National University Polyclinics.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Poon |first1=Chian Hui |title=Public healthcare sector to be reorganised into 3 integrated clusters, new polyclinic group to be formed |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/public-healthcare-sector-to-be-reorganised-into-3-integrated-clusters-new |accessdate=7 July 2019 |website=The Straits Times |date=18 January 2017}}</ref>\n* 20 January - The sleeper replacement project on the [[North South MRT line|North South]] and [[East West MRT line|East West]] lines are completed, resulting in longer lasting concrete sleepers.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Loh |first1=Chuan Junn |title=SMRT sleeper replacement complete, speed limits to be lifted |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/smrt-sleeper-replacement-complete-speed-limits-to-be-lifted-7571200 |website=Channel NewsAsia |date=20 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028130140/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/smrt-sleeper-replacement-complete-speed-limits-to-be-lifted-7571200 |archive-date=28 October 2017 |accessdate=19 January 2020}}</ref>\n* 21 January \u2013 The launch of homegrown bike sharing firm [[oBike]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/new-bike-sharing-system-gets-rolling |title=New bike-sharing system gets rolling |last=Cheong |first=Danson |date=21 January 2017 |website=The Straits Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810212155/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/new-bike-sharing-system-gets-rolling |archive-date=10 August 2017 |url-status=live |language=en |access-date=10 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Since then, [[Ofo (bike sharing)|Ofo]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cheong |first1=Danson |title=New bike-share scheme hits the road |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/new-bike-share-scheme-hits-the-road |accessdate=10 August 2019 |website=The Straits Times |date=18 February 2017}}</ref> [[Mobike]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Chinese firm Mobike rolls into Singapore's bike-sharing market |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/chinese-firm-mobike-rolls-into-singapore-s-bike-sharing-market-8581486 |accessdate=10 August 2019 |website=Channel NewsAsia |date=22 March 2017}}</ref> SG Bike,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hong |first1=Jose |title=Newly launched bike-sharing firm SG Bike plans to take aim at indiscriminate parking |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/newly-launched-bike-sharing-company-aims-to-target-indiscriminate-parking |accessdate=10 August 2019 |website=The Straits Times |date=24 August 2017}}</ref> GBikes<ref>{{cite news |title=New entrant GBikes to share 3,000 bicycles |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/new-entrant-gbikes-to-share-3000-bicycles |accessdate=10 August 2019 |website=The Straits Times |date=18 September 2017}}</ref> and other providers have launched in the following months, leading to the scrapping of the proposed national bike sharing scheme.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/plans-for-national-bike-sharing-scheme-scrapped-as-presence-of-companies-providing-such |title=Plans for national bike sharing scheme scrapped as presence of companies providing such services increases |date=24 March 2017 |website=The Straits Times |archive-date=25 January 2019 |access-date=6 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190125020301/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/plans-for-national-bike-sharing-scheme-scrapped-as-presence-of-companies-providing-such |url-status=live |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 24 January - The [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Singapore)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] announced that all nine [[Terrex ICV|Terrexes]] will return to Singapore after being detained in Hong Kong.<ref>{{cite web |title=Detained Terrexes to return to Singapore: MFA |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/detained-terrexes-to-return-to-singapore-mfa-7556798 |accessdate=15 September 2019 |website=Channel NewsAsia |date=24 January 2017}}</ref> The vehicles arrived back in Singapore on 30 January 2017.<ref>{{cite web |title=SAF Terrex vehicles arrive in Singapore after being detained in Hong Kong |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/saf-terrex-vehicles-arrive-in-singapore-after-being-detained-in--7550656 |accessdate=15 September 2019 |website=Channel NewsAsia |date=30 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n===February===\n* 6 February \u2013 Laws are passed to ban short-term [[renting]] services such as [[Airbnb]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/parliament-short-term-home-rental-illegal-under-new-law|title=Parliament: Short term home rental illegal under new law|date=2017-02-06|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-07-04}}</ref>\n* 9 February \u2013 The Committee of Future Economy releases its report, highlighting seven strategies to transform Singapore's economy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/committee-on-the-future-economy-outlines-7-strategies-to-take-singapore-forward|title=Committee on the Future Economy outlines 7 strategies to take Singapore forward|last=hermesauto|date=2017-02-09|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181019134721/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/committee-on-the-future-economy-outlines-7-strategies-to-take-singapore-forward|archive-date=2018-10-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 17 February \u2013 The name [[Syonan-to]] is dropped from the [[Old Ford Factory]] exhibition after a controversy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/syonan-gallery-renamed-yaacob-apologises-for-pain-the-name-cause-7585602|title=Syonan Gallery renamed, Yaacob apologises for 'pain the name caused'|date=2017-02-17|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2019-07-02}}</ref>\n* 18 February \u2013 \n**Tuas Viaduct is opened to traffic, making it Singapore's first road-rail viaduct.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Abdullah |first1=Zhaki |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/new-tuas-viaduct-to-open-on-feb-18-tuas-west-mrt-extension-to-open-q2-of-2017 |title=New Tuas viaduct to open on Feb 18; Tuas West MRT extension to open in